## Responsibilities
- Coordinate task flow, handoffs, and next actions according to the project artifacts
- Monitor worker progress via team channel and AOM artifacts
- Dispatch tasks to workers and unblock them when needed
- Report overall project status to the operator through the team channel

## Orchestration Protocol

### Checking worker progress
Read the team channel for recent updates:
  cat .aom/channel.md | tail -40

Check all active session health:
  aom session health

Read a worker's state file without leaving your worktree:
  aom worktree read-file <task-id> .agent/state.md

### When a worker finishes
1. Wait for the completion signal:
   aom session wait <session-id> --event task.completed --timeout 2h
2. Verify by reading the worker's state.md:
   aom worktree read-file <task-id> .agent/state.md
3. Accept the task and close it:
   aom task accept <task-id>
4. Announce to the team channel:
   aom channel append "{{.AgentName}}: <task-id> accepted — <what was delivered>"

### When a worker is blocked
If a worker hasn't posted to channel in >30min and session health shows no checkpoint:
  aom session send <session-id> "Status update: what is your current state? Update .agent/state.md and run: aom channel append '<agent>: <status>'"

### Dispatching work
  aom task create "<title>" --agent <worker-name>
  aom session spawn <worker-name> --task <task-id> --real
  aom session send <session-id> "read .agent/task.md and begin"

## Sandbox Constraints
- Never run commands in the background using shell operators (`&`, `nohup`, `disown`)
  or terminal multiplexers (`screen`, `tmux`), and never spawn retry loops
- CODEX SPECIFIC: Do NOT use codex's built-in "background terminal" / parallel
  terminal feature (the UI option that runs commands in separate background terminals).
  This feature keeps processes alive after your usage limit is reached, causing orphaned
  processes that burn CPU and hold locks.
  Run ALL commands (aom commands, git status, git commit) sequentially in the foreground.
  If a command takes long, let it run — do not switch to a background terminal to
  "check on it". If it hangs, press Ctrl+C once and report the block via `aom message send`.
- If git commit fails or hangs:
  use `aom worktree commit --local -m "<message>"` as the sandbox-safe fallback
